[[Sweden]] is one of the world's most [[secularity|secular]] and [[irreligion|irreligious]] nations,<ref>{{cite news|title= DOES SWEDEN DISCRIMINATE AGAINST CHRISTIANS? |work= [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=|url= https://www.vice.com/read/does-sweden-discriminate-against-christians-0000107-v20n10 |accessdate=2014-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitzer.edu/academics/faculty/zuckerman/Zuckerman_on_Atheism.pdf |title=Atheism, Secularity, and Well-Being: How the Findings of Social Science Counter Negative Stereotypes and Assumptions |author=Phil Zuckerman |publisher=Oitzer.edu |accessdate=2014-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228104545/http://www.pitzer.edu/academics/faculty/zuckerman/Zuckerman_on_Atheism.pdf |archivedate=2014-12-28 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20100110/24298 |title= Swedish church losing 1 million members by 2020|publisher=Local |date= |accessdate=2013-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20110615/34370 |title= Swedish Church members 'don't believe in Jesus' |publisher=Local |date= |accessdate=2013-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epjournal.net/wp-content/uploads/EP07398441_c.pdf |title=Evolutionary Psychology: Original Article/Essay |publisher=Epjournal.net |accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norc.org/PDFs/Beliefs_about_God_Report.pdf |title=Beliefs about God across Time and Countries |publisher=-Norc.org |accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z1hbaAHsAlUC&pg=RA1-PA185 |title=Atheism and Secularity - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date=2009-12-21 |accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= What Alabamians and Iranians Have in Common |publisher= [[WIN/GIA|Gallup]]|date=|url= http://www.gallup.com/poll/114211/alabamians-iranians-common.aspx/%22%20/t%20%22_blank|accessdate=2013-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pitzer.edu/academics/faculty/zuckerman/Ath-Chap-under-7000.pdf |title=Atheism: Contemporary Rates and Patterns |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-07-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612114443/http://www.pitzer.edu/academics/faculty/zuckerman/Ath-Chap-under-7000.pdf |archivedate=2009-06-12 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norc.org/PDFs/Beliefs_about_God_Report.pdf |title=Beliefs about God across Time and Countries |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-07-04}}</ref> partly because many Swedish people define themselves as irreligious but [[spirituality|spiritual]] people.<ref>{{cite news|title= Scandinavian Nonbelievers, Which Is Not to Say Atheist |publisher= The New York Times|date=|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/28/us/28beliefs.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> [[Phil Zuckerman]], an Associate Professor of Sociology at [[Pitzer College]],<ref name=Zuckerman>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitzer.edu/academics/faculty/zuckerman/ |title=Phil Zuckerman, Professor of Sociology - Faculty Profiles - Pitzer College |publisher=Pitzer.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> writes that several academic sources have in recent years placed [[atheism]] rates in Sweden between 46% and 85%, with one source reporting that only 17% of respondents self-identified as "atheist".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=tAeFipOVx4MC&dq=%22cambridge+companion+to+atheism%22&pg=PP1 |title=The Cambridge Companion to Atheism |editor=Michael Martin |chapter=Atheism&mdash;Contemporary numbers and Practices |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tAeFipOVx4MC&pg=PA47 |pages=47–50 |last=Zuckerman |first=Phil |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=2006 |isbn=0-521-84270-0 |accessdate=2007-11-15}}<!-- for an earlier version of this, with supporting cites listed, see https://web.archive.org/web/20070813233839/http://www.pitzer.edu/academics/faculty/zuckerman/atheism.html --></ref> A Gallup Poll in 2016 found that 18% of Swedes self report as atheist and 55% as non-religious.[http://gallup.com.pk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Global-Report-on-Religion-2.pdf]
Sweden's official website asserts that just three out of 10 Swedes state that they have confidence in the church. The article lists the following facts about religion in Sweden: * Only 1 in 10 Swedes thinks religion is important in daily life. * Only 1 in 10 Swedes has trust in a religious leader.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20150102/one-in-ten-swedes-trust-religious-leaders|title=Only one in ten Swedes trusts religious leaders|publisher=Thelocal.se|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref>
Statistics from the [[Church of Sweden]] states that: * Under 5 out of 10 children are christened in the church.<ref name="svenskakyrkan-statistics">{{cite web |url=https://www.svenskakyrkan.se/statistik |title=Svenska kyrkan i siffror |website=Svenska kyrkan |language=sv }}</ref> * Around 1 out of 3 weddings take place in church.<ref name="svenskakyrkan-statistics"/> * Around 3 out of 4 Swedes have Christian burials.<ref name="svenskakyrkan-statistics"/>
Many Swedes attend church due to traditional or cultural reasons, but are otherwise not practicing Christians. One poll found that only 15% of [[Church of Sweden]] members actually believe in Jesus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20110615/34370 |title=Swedish Church members 'don't believe in Jesus' - The Local |website=Thelocal.se |date= |accessdate=2016-01-28}}</ref>
Relatedly, the Swedish government has passed several secular reforms over the years; a legal opt-out of the previously mandatory 1.1% [[Church tax#Sweden|church tax]] was allowed in 1951, automatic birthright membership in the [[Church of Sweden]] - the organization's enrollment practice since the 1850s - ended in 1996, and the Church of Sweden was formally separated from the state in 2000, leaving Sweden as "the only [[Nordic country]] without a [[state church]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/31/world/swedes-end-long-union-of-church-and-state.html|title=Swedes End Long Union Of Church And State|agency=Associated Press|publisher=The New York Times|date=1995-12-31|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20150413/swedes-least-religious-in-western-world|title=Sweden 'least religious' nation in Western world|author=|publisher=[[The Local]]|date=2015-04-13|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sweden.se/society/10-fundamentals-of-religion-in-sweden/|title=10 fundamentals of religion in Sweden|author=Scott Sutherland|publisher=[[Swedish Institute]]|date=2015-08-28|accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref>
