===Shinto=== [[File:Qiqihar Shrine.JPG|thumb|150px|Japanese Shinto shrine of [[Qiqihar]], [[Heilongjiang]] (photo taken prior to 1945).]] During the period of the [[Japanese invasion of Manchuria|Japanese occupation]] (1931) and the ''[[Manchukuo]]'' (1932–1945) the [[Japan]]ese conducted scholarly research on the local folk religion{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=53}} and established [[Shinto shrines]], although without trying to impose [[Shinto]] on the native populations as it was the case in [[Korea under Japanese rule|occupied Korea]] and [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|occupied Taiwan]], as the Manchurian State was conceived as a spiritually autonomous nation.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|pp=56-57}}
Many [[Japanese new religions]], or independent [[Shinto sects and schools|Shinto sects]], proselytised in Manchuria establishing hundreds of congregations. Most of the missions belonged to the [[Omoto teaching]], the [[Tenri teaching]] and the [[Konko teaching]] of Shinto.<ref>{{cite book |last = Stalker |first = Nancy K. |year = 2008 |title = Prophet Motive: Deguchi Onisaburō, Oomoto, and the Rise of New Religions in Imperial Japan |publisher = University of Hawaii Press |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9IcxT_DsxN4C |isbn = 0824832264 |ref = harv}} p. 164</ref> The Omoto teaching is the Japanese near equivalent of Guiyidao, as the two religions have common roots and history. {{clear}}
==Abrahamic religions== ===Christianity=== According to the Chinese General Social Survey of 2009, [[Christianity]] is the religion of 2.15% of the population of the region.<ref name="Wang2015"/> Many Christians are reportedly [[Koreans in China|Koreans]].<ref>''Dui Hua'', issue 46, Winter 2012: ''[http://duihua.org/wp/?p=5313 Uncovering China’s Korean Christians]''.</ref> Christianity has a strong presence in the [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture]], in [[Jilin]].<ref>Joel Carpenter, Kevin R. den Dulk. ''Christianity in Chinese Public Life: Religion, Society, and the Rule of Law''. Palgrave Pivot, 2014. {{ISBN|1137427876}}. pp. 29-31</ref> The Christianity of Yanbian Koreans has a patriarchal character; Korean churches are usually led by men, in contrast to Chinese churches which more often have female leadership. For instance, of the 28 registered churches of [[Yanji]], only three of which are Chinese congregations, all the Korean churches have a male pastor while all the Chinese churches have a female pastor.<ref name="Joel Carpenter 2014. p. 33">Joel Carpenter, Kevin R. den Dulk. ''Christianity in Chinese Public Life: Religion, Society, and the Rule of Law''. Palgrave Pivot, 2014. {{ISBN|1137427876}}. p. 33</ref>
Moreover, Korean church buildings are stylistically very similar to [[South Korea]]n churches, with big spires surmounted by large red crosses.<ref name="Joel Carpenter 2014. p. 33"/> Yanbian Korean churches have been a matter of controversy for the Chinese government because of their links to South Korean churches.<ref>Joel Carpenter, Kevin R. den Dulk. ''Christianity in Chinese Public Life: Religion, Society, and the Rule of Law''. Palgrave Pivot, 2014. {{ISBN|1137427876}}. p. 37</ref> {{multiple image | align = center | direction = horizontal | width = 150
