{{Canadian cuisine}}
{{Refimprove|date=November 2013}}
'''St. Catherine's Taffy''' is a variety of [[Taffy (candy)|taffy]] made in [[Quebec]] to celebrate the feast day of [[Saint Catherine of Alexandria]].

==Origins==
St. Catherine's Taffy is a candy made by girls in [[Quebec]] to honour [[Saint Catherine of Alexandria|St. Catherine]], the [[patron saint]] of unmarried women on her [[feast day]], November 25.<ref name="tableq">{{cite news |last=Banjack |first=Bette |url= http://www.phoenixvillenews.com/article/PV/20160317/NEWS/160319981 |title=THE TABLE: Quebec, Canada |work=The Phoenix Reporter & Item |date=2016-03-17 |accessdate=2016-06-15}}</ref> St. Catherine's day is sometimes known in Quebec as "taffy day," a day when marriage-age girls would make taffy for eligible boys. [[Marguerite Bourgeoys]], a founder of the [[Notre-Dame de Montréal]] and an early teacher at Ville-Marie, the colonial settlement that would later become Montreal is credited with starting the tradition as a way of keeping the attention of her young students.

